In Europe it was always accepted that the wife will convert to her husband's religion, e.g. St. Alexandra Feodorovna (the last Russian empress) is an Orthodox saint now, but she was born in Darmstadt in Germany and baptized a Lutheran originally. It was just how things were done.

In the pre-1648 period you had a few anomalies like Henry IV of France having to get married standing outside the church, because they would not let him inside as a Huguenot, but in those times they were treating them more like political parties than actual religions like today.

And it was accepted that the wife would be absolutely loyal to her husband afterwards, once they were married there was no spying and sending letters with information back home or anything, even if the two kingdoms were at war she would support her husband against her homeland.

My family has owned multiple dogs that lived to 15 years or so and died of old age in good health and no one could even conceptualize dog dentistry being a thing, there's an entire fake industry of scamming dog owners with bullshit that works worse than just throwing them a bone.

Taking your dog to a dog dentist to clean its teeth under anesthesia would be considered a level of wastefulness that could only exist in absurdist comedy movies in 99% of the world, you can guarantee the same people promoting this stuff also think giving dogs bones is dangerous.
